"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多电视评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/red-white-royal-blue-review-prime-video-uma-thurman-nicholas-galitzine-taylor-zakhar-perez-67a80cb8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“红、白、宝蓝”评论：亲密的国际关系</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 10 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-planet-review-alien-characters-human-world-nathan-pyle-dan-harmon-apple-tv-586b1510?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《奇异星球》评论：外星人物、人类世界</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 8 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-flowers-of-alice-hart-review-thorny-drama-on-the-australian-prairie-781af5e8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《爱丽丝·哈特的失落之花》评论：澳大利亚大草原上的棘手戏剧</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 3 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《The Wild Sides》评论：最激烈的生存</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 3 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>利普曼-斯特恩和佩斯帕斯先生当时已经在那里工作了很多年，他们打电话、欺骗乡巴佬、贩毒，并帮助把工作场所变成一个兄弟会的房子，一个角色称之为“一群罪犯”——过去、现在和缓刑期间。正如 CDG 的一位资深电话推销员拉里·拉扎尔 (Larry Lazare) 所观察到的那样，“CDG 提供公共服务几乎是偶然的，即为失业者提供就业机会。”换句话说，有犯罪记录的人的工作涉及为执法筹集资金。如果员工表现不佳并被解雇，其缓刑官员将收到通知。</p><p>电影制片人很少得到他们的次要目标警察兄弟会的合作，这是一个全国性组织，其各个分会都是 CDG 的客户；一些主动提出接受采访的 FOP 官员在最后一刻退出了。一些在镜头前比较合法的受访者——美国联邦贸易委员会消费者保护局前局长戴维·弗拉德克 (David Vladeck)；安·拉威尔（Ann Ravel），联邦选举委员会前成员；资深消费者记者莎拉·克莱纳（Sarah Kleiner）坦率地表示，过去或现在将任何警察组织卷入电话营销诈骗的可能性很小，尽管他们钦佩利普曼-斯特恩和佩斯帕斯团队所做的努力，他们缺乏新闻资历，但长期致力于神经。当其他人本想转身而去时，他们却顽强地坚持着。他们甚至与康涅狄格州参议员理查德·布卢门撒尔进行了面对面的会面，后者承诺采取行动，但无法足够快地离开房间。至少他出现了。</p><p>利普曼-斯特恩先生（与他的表弟洛先生一起绘制调查线索）想要拍一部电影。非常有趣、受损但迷人的佩斯帕斯先生也是如此。但后者也追求别的东西，尽管《电话推销员》是对那些用电话毁了你的晚餐、骗老人“烟钱”的人的打击，但它也是对人类的证明。精神——正是这种令人厌烦的情绪，佩斯帕斯先生可能会大笑起来。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。安德森是《华尔街日报》的电视评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 21:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/telemarketers-review-phony-phone-calls-hbo-29d70f21</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/telemarketers-review-phony-phone-calls-hbo-29d70f21<category>艺术评论</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电视节目制作</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业社会责任</category><category>环境/社会/治理</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>慈善/志愿服务</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业社会责任</category><category>环境的</category><category>社会的</category><category>治理</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>慈善机构</category><category>志愿服务</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电视节目制作</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Gran Turismo’ Review: From Game Controller to Steering Wheel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>阿奇·马德奎、奥兰多·布鲁姆和大卫·哈伯主演了一部根据真实故事改编的电影，讲述了一名年轻人的真实故事，他在 PlayStation 视频游戏中的技能导致了职业赛车手的职业生涯。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138162522653780"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833298?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿奇·马德奎</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：索尼影业</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138162522653780"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">凯尔·史密斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 5:35 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gran-turismo-review-orlando-bloom-david-habour-sony-playstation-4e17f79d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>赛车题材电视剧《Gran Turismo》以索尼 PlayStation 游戏为基础，由索尼旗下哥伦比亚影业公司发行，其中提出了一个我以前从未听说过的概念：“登上领奖台”。这意味着进入前三名，根据一位脾气暴躁的教练的说法，只有那些“登上领奖台”的人才能喝香槟庆祝。令人费解。在世界职业棒球大赛中获得第二名的球队是否会进入凯歌香槟？在这张照片之前，获得第二名或更低的成绩通常被称为“失败”，但我怀疑《Gran Turismo》正在向其主角和它自己发出适度的野心：它会满足于被称为第三好的体育失败者电影今年的。</p><p>企业协同效应的电影部分弥漫着一种普遍的感觉，即事情不会朝着太​​令人兴奋的方向发展（日产也深度参与其中，其标志装饰在电影中）。该剧根据来自威尔士的年轻电子游戏玩家 Jann Mardenborough（Archie Madekwe 饰）的真实故事改编，他在家里的驾驶模拟器上熟练地玩《Gran Turismo》后，赢得了日产营销主管梦想的一场比赛（此处为打电话给丹尼·摩尔（奥兰多·布鲁姆饰演），以提高汽车销量。 《GT 学院》是一档电视真人秀节目，游戏玩家被放入真正的赛车中，看看他们是否能够将自己的游戏机技能适应生死攸关的现实。</p><p> 《Gran Turismo》由尼尔·布洛姆坎普（《第九区》、《超查派》）执导，虽然缺乏想象力，但能力十足，是一个相当令人振奋的故事，讲述了一个无名小卒如何接受脾气暴躁但充满爱心的顾问（大卫·哈伯饰）的指导，通过大量的努力训练蒙太奇设置为响亮的音乐（显然，对于驾驶员来说，做大量的俯卧撑和上下楼梯是必不可少的），仔细聆听诸如“专注！”之类的明智建议。和“承诺！”经过许多痛苦的挫折后，最终成为一名职业赛车手。或者，即使没有获胜，至少也登上了领奖台。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833299?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥兰多·布鲁姆和大卫·哈伯</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：索尼影业</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>布洛姆坎普通过俯冲镜头和巧妙的剪辑塑造了激动人心的比赛场景，但充实故事和人物似乎并没有让他或他的编剧杰森·霍尔和扎克·贝林感兴趣。他们甚至没有尝试在“洛基”的配方中添加新元素，而且像往常一样，西尔维斯特·史泰龙应该获得版税检查。考虑到影片的时长（超过两个小时），它的细节令人惊讶地薄弱：驾驶的技术和战术方面几乎都被忽略了，我们从电影中学到了关于赛车的任何东西，除了（正如我们被告知的那样）两次（总共两次），如果前面有一辆车紧贴内侧轨道，你必须转向绕过它。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多电影评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/king-coal-review-documentary-mining-for-stories-in-appalachia-fbefbf36?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“煤炭之王”评论：在阿巴拉契亚挖掘故事</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 10 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-biopics-of-the-21st-century-oppenheimer-ef971e66?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">21 世纪最佳传记片——迄今为止</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 8 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dreamin-wild-review-casey-affleck-zooey-deschanel-walton-goggins-227d1130?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《梦想狂野》评论：当过去的旋律重新浮现</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 3 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teenage-mutant-ninja-turtles-mutant-mayhem-review-coming-out-of-their-shells-again-f90305db?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《忍者神龟：突变混乱》评论：再次破壳而出</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 2 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>马德奎先生是一个讨人喜欢的存在，害羞而尴尬，但他的詹恩也缺乏幽默感、平淡、缺乏动机。他最显着的怪癖是他喜欢在比赛前听 Kenny G 的歌曲。有一个恋人（梅芙·考蒂尔-利利饰），但在他成为名人并邀请她参加相当于他们第一次约会的东京盛大旅行之前，两人几乎不认识。詹恩的父亲（杰蒙·翰苏饰）对此的认识稍好一些，他曾是一名足球运动员，现在在铁路站工作，他推动詹恩走向比体育更实际的职业生涯。谁能责怪他呢？在电影之外，“追随你的梦想”很少是最好的建议。然而，在电影中，这只是陈词滥调，而《Gran Turismo》无疑是一部适合喜欢陈词滥调或太年轻而不会觉得无聊的人的电影。</p><p>由于它也是一份企业新闻稿，因此回避了本应是强有力的考虑因素。布鲁姆先生的角色几乎没有花一点时间考虑他的营销噱头是否导致了 2015 年德国纽博格林一场比赛中一名观众的死亡：作为一名新手车手，马登伯勒把他的车翻了，车子冲出了赛道和围栏。我们被告知，这只是一场不幸的事故，任何人都可能发生，但经验丰富的司机会表现得更好吗？哈伯先生的赛车教练，表面上强硬但实际上心胸宽广的杰克·索尔特（Jack Salter）断言，马登堡必须继续前进，因为“赛车是危险的”。但对于粉丝来说，情况不应该如此。道德责任问题——道德责任问题是电影中的一个关键元素，比这部电影更有趣，或者更不被公司净化——被简单地忽略了。在那些不认真对待这项运动或对其进行任何深度探索的赛车电影中，我非常喜欢《塔拉迪加之夜》。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 21:35:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/gran-turismo-review-orlando-bloom-david-habour-sony-playstation-4e17f79d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/gran-turismo-review-orlando-bloom-david-habour-sony-playstation-4e17f79d<category>艺术评论</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电影制作</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>赛车</category><category>赛车运动</category><category>电影</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>赛车</category><category>赛车运动</category><category>电影</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电影院电影制作</category><category>媒体</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A New Omicron Subvariant, Dubbed ‘Eris,’ Heralds Covid-19’s Resurgence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我们对美国最常见的亚变体 EG.5 的了解<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833284?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">曼哈顿的一个弹出式 Covid-19 测试帐篷。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的加比·琼斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brianna-abbott" itemprop="url" rel="author">布莱恩娜·阿博特</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-kamp" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·坎普</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-s-hopkins" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·S·霍普金斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 3:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>现在还不要指望 Covid-19 被排除在外。</p><p>随着 Omicron 变种的另一个分支势头强劲，美国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Covid-19 感染人数</a>正在上升——在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-influenza-covid-19-tripledemic-this-winter-11667560508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">呼吸道疾病</a>通常会激增的秋季之前。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-do-we-actually-know-about-covid-19-not-enough-ec1dcafe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">该病毒的持续进化</a>提醒人们，尽管这种疾病的破坏性远不如以前，但 Covid-19 仍然对许多人来说是一个麻烦，对一些人来说仍然是一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/long-covid-symptoms-recovery-not-over-2e535790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">严重的风险</a>。废水中病毒浓度的不断上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/face-mask-mandates-fall-away-among-many-hospitals-doctors-6ecaa3e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">医院感染的</a>增加表明，Covid-19 仍然难以预测。</p><p>这种名为 EG.5 的新亚变体是另一个名为 XBB.1.9.2 的变体的后代，据世界卫生组织称，自 8 月 7 日以来，至少有 51 个国家报告了该变体，该组织将 EG.5 归类为本周感兴趣的一个变体。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833823?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> X（以前称为 Twitter）上的一些科学家将其非正式地称为“Eris”。世界卫生组织表示，与其他 Omicron 亚变体一样，EG.5 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/omicrons-trajectory-shows-challenge-of-maintaining-immune-defenses-11651829400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">具有免疫逃逸特性</a>，但没有迹象表明它更严重。</p><p>据美国疾病控制与预防中心称，截至 8 月 5 日，EG.5 预计约占美国病例的 17%，使其成为美国最流行的病毒版本。它是由十多个 Omicron 分支组成的动物园之一，估计至少占病例的 1%。</p><p>路易斯安那州卫生官员兼路易斯安那州卫生部医疗主任约瑟夫·坎特博士表示，由于没有足够的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-director-rochelle-walensky-politicization-science-9c291c7e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检测和测序数据</a>，疾病预防控制中心无法再对美国每个地区进行变异预测。</p><p> “我们预计 EG.5 将继续发挥重要作用，”坎特说。</p><p>卫生官员、疫苗制造商和医生正在为秋季疫苗接种活动做准备，这次活动将与之前的活动有所不同：疫苗将通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-plans-for-end-of-covid-19-shot-treatment-coverage-11660838418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">商业市场</a>而不是政府购买分发给药房和医生办公室。这些疫苗针对的是最近占主导地位的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-covid-shots-in-the-u-s-will-target-omicron-offshoot-xbb-1-5-35e212a0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">XBB.1.5 菌株，</a>符合美国食品和药物管理局今年早些时候制定的指示。</p><p>坎特说，针对 XBB.1.5 更新的助推器应该保留针对 EG.5 的良好保护，因为 Omicron 子变体是相似的。他说，很难预测这种保护会持续多久。</p><p>辉瑞<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfizers-covid-boost-crashes-to-earth-51e1d0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">首席执行官艾伯特·布尔拉 (Albert Bourla)</a>本月表示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PFE" class="company-name">辉瑞</a>预计其新疫苗将于本月获得批准，疫苗接种可能于 9 月开始。辉瑞公司发言人表示，预计该增强剂能够对抗 EG.5，因为它是 Omicron 的一个分支，但正在进行实验室测试以确保这一点。辉瑞和合作伙伴<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BNTX" class="company-name">BioNTech</a>在 6 月份的会议上向 FDA 顾问介绍了如何更新疫苗的动物测试。</p><p> FDA 不太可能要求制造商生产针对 EG.5 的疫苗，因为供应无法及时准备好以供秋季活动使用。辉瑞和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MRNA" class="company-name">Moderna</a>至少需要三个月的时间才能针对 Covid-19 进行 mRNA 注射。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>发言人表示，Moderna 的更新疫苗供应充足，正在等待 FDA 批准分配剂量。他说，初步测试表明该镜头对 EG.5 有效，更多测试正在进行中。</p><p>一位发言人表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVAX" class="">Novavax</a>的 Covid-19 疫苗使用了不同的技术，该公司正在向监管机构提交数据以授权其加强剂，并预计在 9 月份获得许可并发货。</p><p>是否立即接受加强注射或等待新的加强注射<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-you-never-got-covid-19-thank-your-genes-d61c7507?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取决于某人的健康状况和风险</a>， <strong>&nbsp;</strong>威尔康奈尔医学院微生物学和免疫学教授约翰摩尔博士说。他说，患有已有疾病或免疫系统受损的人以及未接种疫苗的人仍然面临高风险。</p><p> “如果您和您的医生认为您现在需要加强注射，请立即注射，”摩尔说。 “这非常有个性。没有一个简单的桶可以容纳每个美国人。”</p><p>去年，RSV 早期严重激增以及流感导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-hospitalizations-babies-young-children-11668080478?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿科医院不堪重负</a>，卫生官员正在为其他呼吸道感染的增加做好准备。 FDA 已<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-vaccine-you-should-get-health-advisers-may-recommend-rsv-shots-60849622?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">批准首款</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-pfizer-rsv-vaccine-rolls-out-into-headwinds-of-hesitancy-74c8aece?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于 60 岁及以上成年人的</a>RSV 疫苗以及一种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于保护婴儿的新药</a>。</p><p> “我们正在进入一个我们并不真正知道这些病毒将如何相互作用的季节，”康涅狄格州公共卫生部专员马尼沙·朱萨尼博士说。</p><p>美国不再像以前那样密切跟踪 Covid-19 感染和住院情况。长期以来，感染情况一直难以记录，因为人们不再在向州卫生当局提供数据的设施中接受检测。医院还取消了对所有患者的常规检测。</p><p>几周来，医院内的 Covid-19 病例一直呈上升趋势。 CDC 表示，截至 7 月底的最新一周内，有 9,056 人因 Covid-19 入院，增长了 12.5%。许多患者因其他原因住院，而不是因为感染，但医院的阳性检测可以反映出社区感染流行率的增加。</p><p> Covid-19 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-million-deaths-the-hole-the-pandemic-made-in-u-s-society-11643662159?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都会导致新的死亡病例</a>，尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-u-s-covid-19-death-toll-is-still-rising-93b2b12a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">远未达到大流行初期的峰值</a>。最近的死亡证明数据显示，美国平均每天有不到 100 例 Covid-19 死亡病例。 2021 年 1 月，一周内每天死亡人数达到历史最高值约 3,700 人。</p><p>写信给 Brianna Abbott（ <a href="mailto:brianna.abbott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">brianna.abbott@wsj.com</a> ）、Jon Kamp（ <a href="mailto:Jon.Kamp@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jon.Kamp@wsj.com</a> ）和 Jared S. Hopkins（ <a href="mailto:jared.hopkins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.hopkins@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260<author><![CDATA[Brianna AbbottJon KampJared S. Hopkins]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>专门药物</category><category>药物</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Maui Wildfires Leave at Least 36 Dead]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>飓风引发的大火摧毁了历史名镇拉海纳<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1E4C7220-8609-4F03-A17C-70F3E330A2CD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">官员称，飓风引发的野火席卷夏威夷毛伊岛，已造成至少 36 人死亡。卫星图像显示了热门​​旅游小镇拉海纳的破坏规模。照片：Matthew Thayer/毛伊岛新闻/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alicia-caldwell" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾丽西亚·A·考德威尔</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-calfas" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹妮弗·卡尔法斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-wright" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·赖特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 1:52（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>夏威夷卡胡卢伊——当局称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-wildfires-maui-big-island-lahaina-hurricane-dora-evacuations-800bf315?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，席卷毛伊岛、摧毁历史名城拉海纳的野火</a>已造成至少 36 人死亡。</p><p>本周早些时候在夏威夷岛上爆发的三场野火是由数百英里外飓风多拉的风力助长的。野火的原因尚未确定。</p><p>拉海纳有超过 271 座建筑遭到损坏或毁坏。拉海纳是夏威夷王国历史悠久的前首都，位于毛伊岛西海岸，现已成为热门旅游目的地。毛伊岛内陆地区（包括哈雷阿卡拉国家公园）至少 1,000 英亩的土地已被烧焦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三，毛伊岛拉海纳市海滨的建筑物、树木和船只被野火摧毁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅森·贾维/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>据联邦紧急事务管理局称，毛伊岛西部约有 11,000 人断电，手机和固定电话服务也已中断。毛伊县官员表示，周三晚间没有针对三场火灾发布新的疏散命令或遏制估计。</p><p> FEMA 表示，截至周四上午，毛伊岛的 6 个避难所已容纳 2000 多人。其中一个避难所位于毛伊岛高中，疏散人员睡在地板上的垫子上。其他人则选择睡在学校停车场的车里。</p><p>周三，伊夫·赫卢 (Yves Helou) 和亚里娜·扬查克 (Yaryna Yanchak) 在拉海纳郊外的酒店缺乏食物和水后，在毛伊岛高中过夜。</p><p>他们表示，由于没有手机服务，他们最初并不知道席卷拉海纳和附近社区的大规模野火。两人说，酒店工作人员只告诉他们，高速公路附近发生了灌木丛火灾。</p><p> “我们是无意中来到这里的，”来自芝加哥的 31 岁的 Helou 说。 “我们只是出去寻找食物。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>由于道路封闭，他们无法进入度假村，他们的行李和扬查克的护照已经回到度假村，两人还无法安排离开毛伊岛。他们希望周四晚些时候离开。</p><p>在联邦团队的支持下，毛伊岛的搜救工作正在进行，8,250 人已被命令撤离该岛。直升机一直在拉海纳上空喷水以控制火势。州和县当局敦促游客远离或离开。夏威夷交通部部长埃德·斯尼芬 (Ed Sniffen) 表示，周三有超过 11,000 名旅客以及约 400 名航空公司工作人员离开毛伊岛。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833199?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三晚上，毛伊岛的卡胡卢伊机场挤满了人，数千人试图离开该岛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：里克·鲍默/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周三晚上，毛伊岛的卡胡卢伊机场挤满了人，数千人试图离开该岛。有些人睡在航站楼里。夏威夷航空运营从机场飞往檀香山的深夜航班，帮助人们撤离该岛。周四，该航空公司增加了 4 趟航班，并提供从毛伊岛出发的 19 美元折扣机票，以帮助紧急离开的人们。</p><p>亚当·温特劳布 (Adam Weintraub) 表示，救援队评估烧毁地区时可能会造成更多人员伤亡。</p>周四，夏威夷紧急事务管理局发言人在“早安美国”节目中。<p></p><p> “我们希望得到最好的结果，但我们也做好了最坏的准备，”他说。</p><p>海岸警卫队表示，已救出14名逃入大海躲避烟雾和火焰的人。</p><p>拜登总统周四宣布夏威夷发生重大灾难，并批准了州长协助应对和恢复工作的请求。州长乔什·格林说，该声明还包括为毛伊县居民寻求临时住房和房屋维修提供资金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="935" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833115?width=1260&amp;height=935" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">夏威夷毛伊岛拉海纳地区 Banyan Court 山火的卫星图像。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maxar Technologies </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="935" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833114?width=1260&amp;height=935" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">野火袭击前的同一地区。在彩色红外卫星图像中，烧毁的区域显示为黑色和灰色，而健康的植被显示为红色阴影。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maxar Technologies</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我保证不遗余力地扑灭破坏性的野火，为流离失所者提供庇护，治疗和安慰受创伤的人，支持我们的急救人员，恢复通讯线路，并争取我们联邦和县合作伙伴的援助，以应对这一历史性的灾难。”一生的灾难，”格林说。</p><p>今年夏天，野火和其他形式的极端天气席卷了世界多个地区。大火席卷了希腊、葡萄牙和加拿大，而中国则面临着严重的洪水和灼热的热浪。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">七月是世界上有记录以来最热的月份</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="672" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ce8ee128-0322-47e6-8c1b-480d6a6040aa-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>拉海纳各地闷烧瓦砾的视频片段显示了破坏的规模。建筑物、棕榈树和汽车被火焰吞没，风吹过的火墙和烟雾蔓延到整个城镇。受灾地区包括前街，这​​是一条深受游客欢迎的不拘一格的道路，两旁遍布商店、企业和历史建筑。</p><p> 1800 年代中期，水手和船只停泊在历史悠久的捕鲸小镇拉海纳。其历史街区是国家历史名胜名录的一部分。据拉海纳修复基金会称，鲍德温故居博物馆是拉海纳的地标，是毛伊岛最古老的房屋。一棵树龄 150 年的巨大榕树是拉海纳市中心的中心景观，于 1873 年被带到岛上。据该镇网站称，这棵树在火灾中受损。</p><p>副州长西尔维娅·卢克周三发布紧急公告，鼓励暂停飞往毛伊岛的所有非必要航空旅行。格林出差归来期间，卢克担任代理州长，他启动了夏威夷国民警卫队以帮助应对工作。</p><p> “我们正在不懈努力，确保每个受影响者的健康和安全，”卢克在参加对损失的空中评估后在周三晚间发表的一份声明中表示。 “虽然我们深爱的拉海纳已经永远改变，但社区的爱和阿罗哈是坚定不移的。”</p><p>周三，夏威夷大岛也发生了三场野火，但当局没有报告任何人死亡。周三晚上，夏威夷县官员取消了与火灾有关的所有强制疏散。</p><p>当局表示，他们已为周二飓风多拉的到来做好准备，但尚未为随后发生的野火做好准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833195?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">视频片段显示，拉海纳的建筑物、棕榈树和汽车被大火吞没。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JEFF MELICHAR/TMX/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>夏威夷国防部副将肯尼思·哈拉少将表示，长期干燥、低湿度和大风助长了野火。</p><p>毛伊岛是夏威夷第二大旅游岛屿，仅次于欧胡岛。根据该州商业、经济发展和旅游部的数据，毛伊岛今年上半年接待游客近 150 万人次，较 2022 年同期增长 5.7%。同期游客总支出为 34.7 亿美元，比去年增长约 25%。</p><p> “这将是一条漫长的复苏之路，”卢克在新闻发布会上说。 “我们对毛伊岛发生的悲剧深感悲痛，尤其是那些失去家人和朋友的人。”</p><p>哈拉指示那些想要寻找亲人的人前往毛伊岛紧急事务管理局。</p><p> — <em>Allison Pohle 对本文做出了贡献。</em></p><p>写信给 Alicia A. Caldwell ( <a href="mailto:alicia.caldwell@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alicia.caldwell@wsj.com</a> )、Michael Wright ( <a href="mailto:michael.wright@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.wright@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Jennifer Calfas ( <a href="mailto:jennifer.calfas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jennifer.calfas@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 17:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7<author><![CDATA[Alicia A. CaldwellJennifer CalfasMichael Wright]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category>野火</category><category>野火</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Red, White & Royal Blue’ Review: Intimate International Relations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在 Prime Video 上，这部根据凯西·麦克奎斯顿畅销 LGBTQ 小说改编的电影中，美国长子与英国王子纠缠在一起，乌玛·瑟曼饰演总统，斯蒂芬·弗莱饰演君主。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136541907386332"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830591?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">泰勒·扎克哈·佩雷斯和尼古拉斯·加利津</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Prime 视频</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136541907386332"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">约翰·安德森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日中午 12:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/red-white-royal-blue-review-prime-video-uma-thurman-nicholas-galitzine-taylor-zakhar-perez-67a80cb8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><strong></strong></p><p>人们应该纵容地凝视一场明亮、聪明、善意的社会政治胡言乱语，它来自成人浪漫的糖果，并提供了自己的剧透：当美国的长子亚历克斯·克莱蒙特-迪亚兹（泰勒扎哈尔·佩雷斯 (Zakhar Perez) 参加了以“红、白、宝蓝”为开场的婚礼，我们首先了解到的是蛋糕价值 75,000 英镑。这很像契诃夫的枪：如果你把一把枪放进故事里，它就一定会响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p><strong>红色、白色和宝蓝色</strong></p><p><strong></strong><em>周五，Prime 视频</em></p></div></div><p>同样，一个价值 75,000 英镑的蛋糕。它很快就会爆炸（它的基座），将亚历克斯、他高贵的对手——专横的亨利王子（尼古拉斯·加利津饰）——以及英美关系本身卷入一场甜蜜、丑闻和面包屑的雨中。我们两国的特殊关系能否经受住这样的灾难的耻辱？有没有更简单的方法让两个角色上床睡觉？这是剧透吗？哦拜托。</p><p>改编自凯西·麦克奎斯顿 (Casey McQuiston) 成功的 LGBTQ 小说，《红、白和宝蓝》是一个如此明显的想法，人们想知道为什么以前没有这样做过——而且它已经这样做了，尽管主角可能不是同性恋。这不能原谅我们两个英俊小伙子漫长的浪漫之旅，也不能原谅一些对话，这比蛋糕对血糖的威胁更大。如果这是一个异性恋故事？它将出现在霍尔马克频道上，只不过在几个奇妙的后现代时刻它能够识别自己的血糖水平。结果真的很搞笑。</p><p> 《红、白、宝蓝》的秘密武器是莎拉·沙希，但要接近她需要一点场景设置。亚历克斯是即将竞选连任的总统埃伦·克莱蒙特（乌玛·瑟曼饰）的儿子；她的丈夫奥斯卡·迪亚兹（小克利夫顿·柯林斯饰）是一个有常识的人，这正是亚历克斯所需要的：自从王子在艾伦上任初期的一次活动中冷落亨利以来，长子一直鄙视亨利，他们的相互蔑视间接导致了非常故意地对糕点暗杀威胁要破坏他妈妈与英国达成的贸易协定（这样的事情可能吗？） 亚历克斯和亨利被迫和好，直到他们决定要和好。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830593?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌玛·瑟曼</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Prime 视频</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“红色、白色和宝蓝色”中充满了不可能性。在一个充斥着王室观察者的世界里，一位继承人（或者他自称“备用”，这让人想起真正的哈里王子）的同性恋行为还能被保密吗？同样，如此一位迷人的年轻人入主白宫，他的性取向难道不会成为媒体密切关注的话题吗？没关系，亚历克斯对自己的性取向如此不确定，而且在这么大的年纪，只有亨利的爱才能帮助他看清自己。 （值得注意的是，他是双性恋。）</p><p>至于沙希女士，她饰演克莱蒙特总统竞选活动的经理扎赫拉·班克斯顿(Zahra Bankston)，竞选活动进展不顺利，突然受到跨大西洋幽会的威胁，可能会产生地震般的影响。扎赫拉在亚历克斯的酒店房间里找到亨利的反应是电影中最好的时刻之一，而且与其他许多时刻不同，这是完全可信的；她期待着“一些随机事件”，结果在壁橱里发现了亨利（是的），并变得气喘吁吁。然后优雅地愤怒。</p><p>当然，这两个恋人必须分开——亨利知道他的责任是对国王（斯蒂芬·弗莱饰）和国家。这几乎令人心碎，亚历克斯在池塘的另一边公开地、频繁地哀悼，扎赫拉最终咕哝着“哦，我的上帝”，并给亨利打电话。她可能看过镜头，但即使她没有看，这个姿势也是专门针对我们观众的，而且是在一个完美的时刻。 “我将不再是耻辱王子，”亨利不久后宣布，显然拒绝与编剧（其中包括导演马修·洛佩兹）分担任何责任，同时为故事锦上添花。它实际上陶醉于自己的可预测性，但也很愚蠢。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。安德森是《华尔街日报》的电视评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 16:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/red-white-royal-blue-review-prime-video-uma-thurman-nicholas-galitzine-taylor-zakhar-perez-67a80cb8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/red-white-royal-blue-review-prime-video-uma-thurman-nicholas-galitzine-taylor-zakhar-perez-67a80cb8<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>政治</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[CPI Report Shows Annual Inflation of 3.2% in July]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>潜在价格压力的稳定月度数据可能会阻止美联储加息。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122083"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><img width="600" height="750" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833214?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122083"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/amara-omeokwe" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿马拉·奥梅奥奎</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 8:51（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国 7 月份年度通胀有所上升，但本月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-cpi-report-inflation-08-10-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜在价格压力</a>仍然温和，可能会阻止美联储在 9 月份加息。</p><p>美国劳工部周四表示，衡量整个经济的商品和服务价格的<a href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">消费者价格指数</a>7 月份同比上涨 3.2%，高于截至 6 月份的全年 3%。所谓的核心价格（不包括波动较大的食品和能源类别）7 月份同比上涨 4.7%，较 6 月份 4.8% 的涨幅略有回落。</p><p>然而，月度数据为当前价格趋势提供了更令人鼓舞的景象。 7月份CPI小幅上涨0.2%，与6月份持平。更好的是，核心 CPI 在两个月内也仅上涨 0.2%，这表明通胀并未开始复苏。美联储官员关注核心通胀，因为他们认为核心通胀比总体通胀率更能预测未来通胀。</p><p>特别是核心消费者物价指数可能会鼓励美联储在 9 月政策会议上维持基准利率稳定。新数据将三个月核心通胀年化率降至 3.1%，这是自 2021 年 3 月以来通胀飙升之前的最低读数。</p><p>美联储官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已将利率提高至 22 年来的高位，</a>以通过冷却经济来降低通胀。他们正在关注通胀和其他经济数据，并权衡是否在九月中旬开会时再次加息。其中包括劳工部关于<a href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">消费者价格指数</a>的报告，这是整个经济中最受广泛关注的商品和服务价格衡量指标之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831800?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美联储官员看到了一些令人鼓舞的迹象，表明价格压力正在缓解。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·扎鲁博夫斯基/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>通货膨胀数学和基本效应</h3><p>《华尔街日报》调查的经济学家估计，7月份CPI环比上涨0.2%，与6月份持平，表明物价压力保持稳定。根据预测，这意味着 7 月份 12 个月通胀率将从 6 月份的 3% 攀升至约 3.3%，这是两年多以来最慢的增速。经济学家表示，这一增长可能与 2022 年 6 月和 7 月发生的情况有很大关系，这是比较的基础。</p><p>年度通胀率于 2022 年 6 月达到 9.1% 的峰值，然后在接下来的几个月中放缓。</p><p>这使得即使月度增长规模保持稳定，今年 7 月的同比比较也可能会出现加速。</p><p>经济学家表示，这种所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-base-effects-trip-up-our-understanding-of-the-economy-66fde398?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">基数效应</a>是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">6 月份年度通胀率较 5 月份下降</a>的部分原因，并且在 2024 年初之前可能不会大幅放缓。他们表示，如果每月价格变化与六月份一样温和，那么未来几个月这一速度可能会加快。</p><p>考虑到这些统计异常，七月份同比增速的增长并不一定表明<strong>&nbsp;</strong>劳拉·罗斯纳 (Laura Rosner) 表示，最近的通胀放缓正在逆转，</p>研究和咨询公司 MacroPolicy Perspectives 的创始人兼高级经济学家。此外，罗斯纳表示，月度增长 0.2% 将被视为符合美联储官员希望看到的温和通胀。<p></p><h3>核心通胀可能保持稳定</h3><p>经济学家估计，所谓的核心价格（不包括波动较大的食品和能源类别）7 月份较 6 月份上涨 0.2%，较上年同期上涨 4.8%，与 6 月份相同。美联储官员关注核心通胀，因为他们认为核心通胀比总体通胀率更能预测未来通胀。</p><p>在经济从疫情中复苏之初，租金和二手车价格大幅上涨。但七月和未来几个月应该会显示<strong>&nbsp;</strong>租金通胀持续放缓和二手车价格下降， <strong>&nbsp;</strong> Nationwide首席经济学家Kathy Bostjancic表示，这将给核心通胀带来下行压力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FB57A5A0-E270-46D2-B5D4-3ED0269F546E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fconsumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">本周发布的内容包括 CPI 通胀报告、UPS 和迪士尼的盈利报告。最新的消费者信贷报告和季度家庭债务数据也在预期之中。 《华尔街日报》的 Dion Rabouin 对此进行了详细分析。照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>美联储还关注什么</h3><p>尽管美联储官员看到了一些令人鼓舞的迹象，表明物价压力正在缓解，但经济<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">却出乎意料地出现了大幅放缓</a>。美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔表示，央行正在寻求劳动力市场进一步疲软，包括工资增长放缓。</p><p>工资压力是美联储也在密切关注通胀指标的部分原因，该指标主要关注不包括能源和住房在内的劳动密集型服务业。所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-is-supercore-inflation-11675195498?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超级核心通胀</a>和整体核心通胀在 7 月份可能不会大幅放缓，因为机票和酒店价格可能没有像 6 月份那样快速降温，他说</p>普贾·斯里拉姆 (Pooja Sriram)，巴克莱银行美国经济学家。<p></p><p>斯里拉姆表示，不包括汽车在内的核心商品通胀趋势也可能表明，早期的供应链问题和大流行造成的其他干扰是否正在继续消退。</p><h3> 7月汽油价格</h3><p>根据能源数据和分析提供商 OPIS 的数据，7 月份美国每加仑普通无铅汽油的平均价格从月初的约 3.54 美元逐渐攀升至月底的 3.76 美元。经济学家表示，由于消费者价格指数基本上是基于本月平均价格，因此近期汽油价格的上涨可能会对八月份的通胀数据产生更大的影响。</p><p>写信给 Amara Omeokwe： <a href="mailto:amara.omeokwe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">amara.omeokwe@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/3edd1a82-cda0-47b5-81bf-89e82fb91993.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670<author><![CDATA[Amara Omeokwe]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Colleges Spend Like There’s No Tomorrow. ‘These Places Are Just Devouring Money.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>学生们为旗舰州立大学买单，这些大学将资金投入到新建筑和项目中，几乎没有受到任何阻力<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833009/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/melissa-korn" itemprop="url" rel="author">Melissa Korn</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andrea-fuller" itemprop="url" rel="author">Andrea Fuller</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-s-forsyth" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jennifer S. Forsyth</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>美国最著名的公立大学一直在无限制地花钱。在过去的二十年里，他们建造了新的天际线，包括时髦的学术建筑和宿舍。他们向大型体育项目投入巨资，并聘请了多层管理人员。</p><p>然后他们将法案传递给学生。</p><p>肯塔基大学将其校园升级为十多年来每天花费 805,000 美元。其新生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/many-colleges-fail-in-push-to-boost-enrollment-of-lower-income-students-11663164001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来自美国最贫穷的州之一</a>，2021-22 学年的入学费用平均为 18,693 美元。</p><p>宾夕法尼亚州立大学花费了太多的钱，现在陷入了预算危机——尽管它是美国最昂贵的公立大学之一</p><p>俄克拉荷马大学的学费上涨幅度最大，同时花费数百万美元用于项目，包括为其海外​​留学项目收购和翻修一座 32,000 平方英尺的意大利修道院。</p><p>这项支出与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nyu-college-graduate-parent-student-loans-11639618241?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国 1.6 万亿美元的联邦学生债务危机</a>有着千丝万缕的联系。大学通过提高学费来投入资金，这让许多学生别无选择，只能承担更多债务。这意味着学生贷款可以为大学项目提供轻松的融资。</p><p> “学生们现在没有资源来继续为大学想做的所有事情买单，”俄克拉荷马州 2023 届毕业生克里斯平·南 (Crispin South) 说。 “你不能仅仅通过向学生求助来继续增加收入。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1500" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/1980839d-de93-4796-9018-4224bb39ebf9-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>美国家庭长期以来都清楚，大学费用已经上涨，即使是那些旨在让州居民负担得起的公立学校也是如此。为了找出根本原因，《华尔街日报》检查了 2002 年以来 50 所旗舰大学（通常是各州最古老的公立学校）的财务报表，并根据通货膨胀进行了调整。</p><p> 2002 年至 2022 年间，中位旗舰大学的支出增长了 38%。</p><p>在《华尔街日报》的分析中，只有一所学校——爱达荷大学——的支出较少。</p><p>学校通过收取学费来支付部分费用。旗舰店的本科生和研究生学杂费收入中位数是 20 年前的两倍多。即使考虑到入学人数的增加，普通学生的物价上涨了 64%，远远超过了大多数家庭开支的增长。</p><h3>更多学费收入</h3><p>公立大学的领导者经常将提高学费收入的需要归咎于国家资金的吝啬。四分之三的州确实削减了支持，破坏了学校在政府支持下教育民众的长期原则。但大学普遍并没有因此勒紧裤腰带。相反，他们提高的价格远远超出了填补漏洞所需的水平。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》发现，过去 20 年来，这些大学的国家支持每损失 1 美元，中等学校的学杂费收入就会增加近 2.4 美元，超过了削减的金额。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1334" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5c3441d8-64ed-4f87-b10e-dbf69fcfa3da-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自始至终，学校都在一种重视持续增长、优先考虑增加收入而不是削减成本的文化中运作。管理人员制定了雄心勃勃的战略计划，并试图用豪华的设施来吸引富裕的学生。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-news-college-rankings-yale-law-fe24f0b2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">有影响力的大学排名奖励</a>那些花费更多的人。</p><p>许多大学官员很难了解自己的预算，只是每年都增加支出。受托人几乎不要求承担任何责任，而且常常对摆在他们面前的事情盖上橡皮图章。而且学校不一致地披露他们的支出情况，使得公众几乎不可能审查他们的学费和税款的使用情况。</p><p> “这些地方只是在吞噬金钱，”2008 年至 2013 年担任北卡罗来纳大学教堂山分校校长、现任《科学》杂志主编的霍顿·索普 (Holden Thorp) 说。他说，一次性向所有人提供一切是不可持续的。 “大学需要关注他们真正的优先事项是什么以及他们创建的目的是什么，”他说。</p><p>大学在课堂内外投入资金，包括改进技术、扩大咨询和校内体育活动，以及建设现代化宿舍和新体育场等设施。</p><p>为了检查公立大学的支出，《华尔街日报》从审计、存档预算网站以及通过公共记录请求收到的文件中收集了涵盖 2002 年、2012 年和 2022 年支出的数据。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》的分析发现，行政人员、教师、教练和财务专家的支出增长大部分体现在招聘过程中。工资和福利通常会占用运营预算的一半以上，但自 2002 年以来，中位旗舰店的工资和福利上涨了约 40%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829618?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，肯塔基大学的学生中心。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829601?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">肯塔基州新电子竞技休息室中用于视频游戏的电脑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>2022年，佛罗里达大学拥有超过50名具有主任、副主任或传播助理主任职称的员工，大约是2017年人数的两倍。该校还聘用了超过160名助理、副院长、执行官和其他类型的院长去年，这一数字较 2017 年的约 130 有所增加。</p><p>发言人史蒂夫·奥兰多表示，该大学是权力下放的，不同部门可以根据需要自由招聘。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》对奈特-纽豪斯学院体育数据库数据的分析发现，2010 年至 2022 年间，旗舰学校经通胀调整后的体育教练支出增加了约一半。 《华尔街日报》使用了数据最完整时期的数据。</p><p>尽管少数实力雄厚的体育系可以自己支付费用， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/march-madness-is-a-moneymaker-most-schools-still-operate-in-red-11615545002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">但大多数只能靠学生学费和大学补贴才能收支平衡</a>。</p><p>在所有有可用数据的旗舰产品中，2022 年的额外资金总额为 6.32 亿美元。这比 12 年前增长了 27%。</p><p>康涅狄格大学今年春天赢得了男子篮球全国冠军，其女子篮球队几乎一直进入四强。然而，自 2016 年以来，康涅狄格州的体育系每年收到超过 3500 万美元的学生费用和大学补贴以维持生计。 2022 年，该基金获得了 5500 万美元的资金，占其体育总预算的一半以上。</p><p>学校表示，其中超过 1300 万美元的补贴用于支付一名前男子篮球教练，作为其雇佣合同法律和解的一部分，并且学校面临着必须支付租金和篮球和曲棍球比赛的其他费用的独特挑战。是在校外进行的。</p><p>总体而言，2002 年至 2022 年间，康涅狄格大学的支出增长了 73%，远远快于入学人数的增长。其中大部分是由人员成本推动的，福利支出增加了两倍多。</p><p>负责预算、规划和机构研究的副校长雷卡·乌林恩(Reka Wrynn)表示，部分原因是该校在该州无资金支持的养老金负债中所承担的责任越来越大。她说，康涅狄格州还有义务支付工会雇员与该州谈判的加薪费用。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829597?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">康涅狄格大学篮球队参加三月份的 NCAA 女子锦标赛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肖恩·埃利奥特/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>责任很少</h3><p>大学在预算方面几乎没有承担任何责任，部分原因是它们不需要以统一的方式跟踪费用。教育部关于大学财务的数据经常包含错误，并且与审计数据不符。</p><p>学校可以自行决定对经审计的财务报表上的支出进行分类，这使得对单个学校在一段时间内或不同学校之间进行精确比较非常困难。例如，大学有时将教授的工资分为一年的教学支出和下一年的研究费用。</p><p>田纳西大学诺克斯维尔分校研究大学财务的教育学教授罗伯特·凯尔琴（Robert Kelchen）表示，大学将审计“更多地视为一种要求，而不是公众的工具”。</p><p> 2002 年至 2012 年间，学校支出增长尤为强劲，总运营支出中位数增长了 30%。在经济衰退和大流行的双重财务压力下，一些学校在接下来的十年里开始缩减支出。在全国范围内对学生债务的强烈抗议中，他们还放慢了学费上涨的速度。</p><p>但支出仍在攀升。从 2012 年到 2022 年，中等大学的总运营费用增长了近 10%。</p><p>在某些情况下，随着学生人数的增长，大学的支出也会增加，典型的旗舰大学在过去二十年里招生人数增加了约 20%。在某些情况下，增加学生可能会很昂贵（需要新的宿舍和教室空间），或者相对便宜，尤其是对于在线学生而言。尽管如此，过去 20 年来，每个学生的支出中位数增加了 15%。</p><p>即使是美国最贫困州的学生，学校也将这笔费用转嫁给学生。大多数学校增加了对低收入学生的经济援助，但这并没有完全抵消许多家庭不断上涨的学费。</p><p>肯塔基州是全国家庭收入中位数最低的州之一。州内学生在 2021-22 年支付的费用使肯塔基州在按费用排名的旗舰学校中名列前茅。这些来自教育部的数据涵盖了新生在获得奖学金后平均支付的学费、杂费、食宿费用。</p><p>肯塔基州在其网站上宣称，在过去的十几年里，其列克星敦校区的翻修总共花费了 36.6 亿美元。其中包括法律、商业和视觉艺术学校的新校舍、最先进的医院设施、学生中心、拥有 900 个停车位的停车场、用于视频游戏比赛的剧院以及配有全尺寸 Tempur-Pedic 运动设施的宿舍床垫、花岗岩台面和内置洗衣干衣机。</p><p>私人开发商参与了一些项目，但总建筑成本的一半以上是由大学资金支付的。</p><p> “我们的宿舍满足学生和家庭的需求和期望，同时强调学习和联系，”大学发言人杰伊·布兰顿说。他说，宿舍的一些功能，例如工作台面，维护费用较低，而且购买 Tempur-Pedic 床垫的成本与传统床垫相当。</p><p>该校几十年前就立志成为全国最好的大学之一。具体来说，根据 1997 年的一项州政府指令，它的目标是跻身开展研究和提供博士学位的前 20 所公立学校之列。尽管有这项指令，立法机关还是开始减少资金。 20多年来，拨款减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829623?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">肯塔基州学生中心的外观，近年来进行了升级和扩建。自2011年以来，学校斥资36.6亿美元改造校园。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829599?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">七月，肯塔基州校园正在施工。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“我们不会削减我们的愿望，”总统埃利·卡皮卢托 (Eli Capilouto) 2016 年表示。“但我们确实必须找到更有创意的方式来推动我们的进步。”肯塔基州增加了研究经费和教师工资，这有助于吸引人才。</p><p>一些大学排名，包括《美国新闻与世界报道》，奖励这些类别的支出以及俱乐部和文化活动等学生服务。他们不一定会赞扬那些让学校变得更有效率的举措。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-rankings-list-2022-11632246093?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《华尔街日报》的大学排名</a>也考虑了支出，但在即将发布的报告中将放弃这一衡量标准。</p><p>尽管肯塔基州做出了巨大的努力，《美国新闻与世界报道》将该校在 2022 年公立大学中排名第 64 位，实际上比十年前的排名下降了一些。</p><p>但学生的账单却增加了。肯塔基州每名学生的学杂费收入比 20 年前增加了约 70%。</p><p> 2017年，罗恩·里德（Rowan Reid）担任肯塔基州学生会主席，并在大学董事会中占有一席之地。当被要求投票支持将州内本科生的学费增加 4% 时，她敦促其他董事会成员让学校承担更多责任。</p><p>里德当时表示：“我们只将效率提高到可以将剩余赤字转嫁给学生的程度。” “对我来说，这感觉不对。”</p><p>学费上涨的比例为 16 比 1，里德是唯一投反对票的人。回顾今年春天她在董事会的经历，里德表示，她的职责是照顾学生的利益，但她不知道如何才能将这一点与对大学最有利的因素结合起来。</p><p>学校表示，过去几年学杂费的增长速度有所放缓，来自最低收入家庭的学生可以获得奖学金支持。</p><p>布兰顿说，肯塔基州继续发展，并渴望被公认为全国最好的公共研究机构之一，但已转向更广泛的重点，以推动该州的发展。</p><h3>争夺最优秀的学生</h3><p>学校在校园里配备了最先进的娱乐中心和宿舍，以吸引考试成绩最高且经济援助需求最低的学生。 The price for these amenities was then baked into the bills for all students, including with fees students paid to cover construction debt.</p><p> Tuition and fee revenue per student climbed by double digits in the past 20 years at every school in the Journal&#39;s analysis. The average student paid more because many schools both upped prices and increased the percentage of higher-paying students from out of state. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="3268" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/4e1b3086-4f54-4f8b-ad64-239b2396927d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> At the University of Oklahoma, per-student tuition and fees rose 166%, the most of any flagship. The school also borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars to perform building upgrades and erect new dormitories.</p><p> “We levered up the balance sheet to avoid dealing with [financial] reality,” said Oklahoma President Joseph Harroz Jr. , who took the helm in 2019. Across higher education, he said, “there was an arms race.”</p><p> Beginning in 2009, the university spent $14.3 million to buy and renovate a monastery in Arezzo, Italy, to house a new study-abroad program. The monastery has a landscaped garden, faculty apartment and classrooms featuring painted frescoes.</p><p> The school said it was paid for by a mix of private gifts and university funds.</p><p> “Would I go and do one of those right now? No,” Harroz said. “It wouldn&#39;t be the best use of capital dollars.”</p><p> Harroz said that under some of his predecessors, the school didn&#39;t maintain long-term budget plans or prioritize its needs over its wishes. Oklahoma has since changed course, he said, and the university cut $143 million in expenses at the main campus in Norman since 2018.</p><p> The increase in tuition at Oklahoma came after the state legislature gave school regents tuition-setting authority in the early 2000s, a move designed to allow the school to catch up with its peers&#39; rates, said University of Oklahoma spokeswoman April Sandefer. She said its increases have slowed in recent years, and more than half of Oklahoma undergraduates leave school debt-free thanks to a growing financial-aid budget.</p><h3> License to spend</h3><p> Research by James V. Koch, an economist who studies college spending and a former president at Old Dominion University in Virginia, found that public-university trustees approved 98% of the cost-increasing proposals they reviewed, often unanimously. In most states, he said, there hasn&#39;t been anyone to say, “No, you can&#39;t do that.”</p><p> Back in 2005, a Hawaii state audit called out the University of Hawaii System board for approving a budget that gave the flagship Manoa campus $200 million when, auditors said, all but $13 million went to vague or unnecessary requests.</p><p> Honolulu attorney Benjamin Kudo, who joined the university&#39;s board in 2011, said he was stunned by the lack of information he was given during the budget process. He said he received a packet of pie charts and a PowerPoint presentation with general information on how the university planned to divide up its funds for areas including teaching, libraries, athletics and facilities across 10 campuses. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829600?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The University of Oklahoma&#39;s campus in Arezzo, Italy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The University of Oklahoma </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829596?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Norman campus at Oklahoma. The school borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars to perform building upgrades and erect new dormitories.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kudo said administrators weren&#39;t initially receptive to requests that he and another new board member, Jan Sullivan, made for more detail, including a comparison of projected versus actual spending. Kudo, who served on the board until 2022, recalled being accused of trying to micromanage the $1 billion budget.</p><p> School officials expected him to follow the lead of prior trustees, Kudo said: “It&#39;s basically an automatic approval of whatever the administration wants.”</p><p> Sullivan also said such rubber stamping was typical early in her tenure. After a few years of nagging, Sullivan and Kudo said, the board received more detailed financial information, and it stopped greenlighting so many requests.</p><p> University of Hawaii President David Lassner said the university has changed. He decried a time around a decade ago, shortly after he was named interim president, when the board found out about depleted reserves by reviewing audited financial statements that had been produced six months after the fiscal year closed.</p><p> “That is no way to understand the financial health of something as big and complicated as this,” he said. “We&#39;re certainly not budgeting by pie charts anymore.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831288?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> University of Hawaii President David Lassner, center, at the ceremony to officially name him president of the school in 2014.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: University of Hawaii</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> &#39;Knee-jerk reaction&#39;</h3><p> Penn State, like many schools, long relied on a simple approach to budgeting, in which each department generally received the same amount of money it got the prior year plus a little more to cover inflation. Dollars were rarely tied to enrollment shifts or demonstrated need.</p><p> The school&#39;s spending rose 36% since 2002. That number excludes the university&#39;s health system, which the Journal removed from its analysis where possible. Total tuition and fee revenue from both undergraduate and graduate students increased 72% over the past two decades, far faster than enrollment grew.</p><p> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus was the country&#39;s most expensive state flagship in the 2021-22 school year for in-state freshmen after scholarships. Those students paid an average $26,747 in tuition, fees, room and board, according to the Education Department data.</p><p> The school said it offers students the option of starting at one of its less expensive regional campuses and finishing at University Park, and has increased financial aid significantly. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1594" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/2b99b9f0-3109-4607-9038-fffbc5ecc301-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Penn State cut spending nearly 3% between 2012 and 2022. Still, the university&#39;s 2022-23 budget forecast spending that was $140 million more than its revenue.</p><p> It&#39;s not the first time expenditures were projected to outpace revenue, and Penn State determined last year it was on track to blow through its $350 million reserve funds in the next few years if it didn&#39;t change course. Trustees gave the administration until 2025 to balance the budget.</p><p> Trustee Barry Fenchak criticized his fellow board members at the meeting when they voted last summer to increase tuition and fees by 5% for in-state students at the University Park campus after the state held funding flat.</p><p> “I think the knee-jerk reaction was, &#39;OK, we&#39;ve got to raise tuition,&#39; and I think perhaps the knee-jerk reaction should have been, &#39;We need to get to work on the things we should&#39;ve been doing for the last 10 years and light a bit of a fire underneath our behinds&#39; ” to address costs, he said.</p><p> Several trustees at the meeting said the decision was based on thorough analysis.</p><p> At meeting after meeting for decades, Penn State board members complained of the state&#39;s anemic support while they simultaneously approved hundreds of millions of dollars in new construction, according to board minutes.</p><p> The university&#39;s state appropriation fell 39% over the past 20 years, and the school receives among the lowest state support per student of US flagships. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831761?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus in April. The school spent so much money that it now has a budget crisis, even though it&#39;s among the most expensive public universities in the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: aul Weaver/Sipa/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Growth in tuition revenue has more than made up for declining state funding. On a per-student basis, Penn State received nearly $2.25 in additional tuition revenue for every $1 lost in state support, compared with $1.25 in tuition revenue added at the median school.</p><p> “We acknowledge that tuition has increased quite a bit over the past 20 years, which is a large stretch of time for such a comparison when taking into account growth in student needs, services, technology, stem fields, academic support, mental health services etc. and considering our stagnant state funding,” said Lisa Powers, a school spokeswoman.</p><p> Mary Isaacson, a Democrat and chair of the subcommittee on higher education in the Pennsylvania House of Representatives, said that while public funding declined, the school&#39;s aggressive physical growth and lengthy wish list also helped put it on its path to financial insecurity.</p><p> Penn State said much of the construction was necessary to replace aging facilities, and that factors such as inflation and the pandemic drove up costs, too.</p><p> The university said last year it would revise the way it sets its operating budget. The new model, it said, will take into account enrollment changes and available resources, and be data-driven.</p><p> Write to Melissa Korn at <a href="mailto:Melissa.Korn@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Melissa.Korn@wsj.com</a> , Andrea Fuller at <a href="mailto:andrea.fuller@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrea.fuller@wsj.com</a> and Jennifer S. Forsyth at <a href="mailto:Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>方法</h4><p>To examine colleges&#39; spending patterns, the Journal supplemented figures from audited financial statements from 2002, 2012 and 2022 with data from public information requests and other documents. All numbers in the analysis were adjusted to 2022 dollars. Figures representing the median flagship were calculated by taking the median of the change at each school.</p><p> Some schools said they didn&#39;t keep historical records of every figure the Journal sought, such as salary and benefits spending. The Journal asked colleges to provide information for only the main flagship campus, but not all schools said they were able to do so. The figures for roughly one third of the universities in the Journal&#39;s analysis include data for some branch campuses, with data for several states representing large university systems.</p><p> The Journal asked colleges to exclude health systems and hospital operations from the figures, but not all did so. Health-related expenses can make up a large share of operating budgets, and universities that included hospitals in their figures tended to have among the largest increases in total operating expenses. However, the overall median increase in operating expenses was roughly similar whether or not the Journal included these schools in its analysis.</p><p> Separately, the Journal used data from the Education Department that covered the price in-state students typically paid. These figures, known as net price, cover the average cost of first-time, full-time students who received scholarships.</p><p> Per-student tuition revenue figures, derived from data in audited financial statements, reflect money paid by all students, including graduate and out-of-state. As a result, these calculations don&#39;t match the net-price figures.</p><p> Enrollment figures, also from the Education Department, reflect what is known as full-time equivalent enrollment. To calculate this, the Journal used a formula similar to the Education Department&#39;s method, taking into account the mix of full- and part-time undergraduate and graduate students each fall.</p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100<author><![CDATA[Melissa KornAndrea FullerJennifer S. Forsyth]]></author><category> wsjinvestigations</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>photo-commission</category><category>教育</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学学院</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Career Education</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>career education </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[When You’re the Boss, but Your Employees Make More Money]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Power dynamics get complicated when managers earn less than their employees <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831727/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Andrea D&#39;Aquino for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (5) <span>Photo Illustration by Andrea D&#39;Aquino for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (5)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118888"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118888"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-498821" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers" itemprop="url" rel="author">Callum Borchers</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 9, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> When NFL quarterback Justin Herbert and NBA star Jaylen Brown signed contracts this summer worth $262.5 million and $304 million, respectively, they struck the richest deals in their leagues&#39; histories. They&#39;re also outearning their bosses by millions a year.</p><p> Professional athletes often command higher salaries than their coaches, since it&#39;s harder to find people to execute plays than diagram them. And individual contributors can earn more than managers in a lot of fields, from finance and tech to sales and media.</p><p> The sticking point is how bosses and their charges deal with those imbalances.</p><p> There are two keys to a functional working relationship when a subordinate makes more money than their manager, people in both camps tell me: The boss must possess the humility to accept the situation and the confidence to project authority. And the highly paid employee can&#39;t be a diva.</p><p> Richard Reice, a labor attorney and chief people officer of a restaurant group, says fat paychecks can lead to entitlement and make a highly paid employee practically unmanageable.</p><p> “Some refuse to do basic things, like attend meetings, just because they think they&#39;re silly,” he says.</p><h3> When leadership doesn&#39;t pay</h3><p> It&#39;s hard to quantify how frequently rank-and-file workers make more than their bosses, but Reice says he has observed a shift from his dual perches in employment law and human resources. Many companies are scrapping the old notion that bigger titles should automatically mean bigger bucks. Instead of promoting star employees into management, where administrative duties can <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/as-we-work/why-middle-managers-are-feeling-the-squeeze-and-how-to-fix-it/12efb5a7-69ab-477e-848a-9550d381c8dc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">siphon time from their true talents</a> , more businesses are keeping top performers in individual-contributor roles—and paying them like bosses.</p><p> Leadership, in these situations, is considered like any other skill, and not necessarily one that is worth more money.</p><p> We&#39;re more likely to notice now when someone outearns the boss. The pandemic-era rise of distributed teams was accompanied by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-want-to-do-their-jobs-from-anywhere-and-keep-their-big-city-salaries-11631282375?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cost-of-living adjustments</a> , which meant a manager based in an inexpensive town might earn less than direct reports living in pricier cities.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/salary-ranges-bring-changes-to-the-job-hunt-11665263465?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Pay-transparency laws</a> have given some bosses the jarring experience of seeing less-senior positions at their companies posted on job boards with advertised salaries that exceed their own. Market demand can explain some discrepancies; in other cases, racial, age or gender <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gender-pay-gap-college-11659968901?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">biases could be to blame</a> .</p><h3> Keep your ego in check</h3><p> Nikki Barua, who runs the women&#39;s leadership program Beyond Barriers, says her clients in managerial positions sometimes feel underpaid relative to subordinates and are unsure whether discrimination is a factor. Bosses need to recognize there are often valid reasons behind pay, she says, and advises managers to pay more attention to what their fellow bosses make. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831916?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nikki Barua runs the women&#39;s leadership program Beyond Barriers.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emily Cummings</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The star performer is not the right comparison,” she says.</p><p> Barua says that in previous roles at technology and consulting firms, her knack for bringing in business sometimes led to incentives that pushed her pay over her managers&#39;. She kept her ego in check by viewing her skill as a blessing, remembering that others might be equally good at different jobs that the labor market rewards less generously.</p><p> Now, as an entrepreneur trying to conserve cash, she&#39;s sometimes paid herself less than her employees. She admits that, at times, it was hard not to resent people making more than she did, feeling that she&#39;d be able to draw a salary if only they&#39;d work harder or do better.</p><p> Founders <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-entrepreneurs-should-pay-themselves-1422244851?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">often draw modest salaries</a> , or none at all, in companies&#39; early days, says Jeff Bussgang, general partner in the Boston office of startup investor Flybridge Capital Partners.</p><p> “Naturally, if they own a big chunk of equity, it makes it all more palatable,” he says.</p><p> Plus, owners&#39; status is seldom in doubt, regardless of pay. Berkshire Hathaway CEO Warren Buffett, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-MBB-36218?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">acquired a controlling stake</a> in the company in 1965, has for several decades taken an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/berkshire-salaries-for-warren-buffett-charlie-munger-unchanged-at-100-000-each-1489790574?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">annual salary of $100,000</a> . His total compensation last year was $401,589, while two vice chairmen earned more than $19 million apiece. Buffett, the world&#39;s sixth-richest person with a net worth of $122 billion, according to the Bloomberg Billionaires Index, derives most of his income from investments.</p><h3> Bosses who earn less</h3><p> Ellen Taaffe, who sits on the compensation committees of several companies, including AARP Services, says corporate boards often set pay by studying the going rates for similar roles in other organizations. Boards can ease potential tension by giving junior executives lower base salaries and enabling them to surpass more senior leaders only through bonuses for exceeding expectations. Usually the people with the loftiest titles make the most money, but not always, notes Taaffe, who teaches at Northwestern University&#39;s Kellogg School of Management.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Have you ever been in a work situation where the boss made less than the employees?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> For instance, the chief scientific officer of a biotech company—whose research might be the crux of the business&#39;s success or failure—could be paid more than the CEO. George Yancopoulos, the chief scientific officer of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/REGN" class="">Regeneron Pharmaceuticals</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> has received almost $435 million in total compensation since 2012, according to securities filings, making him the company&#39;s highest-paid employee over that span. (Regeneron may be best known for its monoclonal antibody treatment for Covid.)</p><p> At some universities, the highest-paid employee isn&#39;t the president; it&#39;s the football coach or the person who manages the endowment. The $2.2 million pay package awarded to Yale University President Peter Salovey last fiscal year was one-third of what the chief investment officer earned, according to tax filings.</p><p> Leaders who successfully handle higher-paid employees find satisfaction in helping others shine, Taaffe says.</p><p> Warren Cereghino, a retired TV news director in California, says he kept pride at bay by reminding himself that viewers tuned in to watch his station&#39;s anchors, who earned more than he did as their boss. He says the on-air talent didn&#39;t abuse their sway.</p><p> Still, being privy to their contracts, he knew that some had negotiated a measure of editorial control in addition to large salaries. If there was a disagreement, he wouldn&#39;t necessarily win.</p><p> “Even though my name was on the door of the news director&#39;s office, there was a limit to my power,” he says.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Theo Francis contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Callum Borchers at <a href="mailto:callum.borchers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">callum.borchers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/12865c40-068f-4100-aa18-f73fd5f66fae.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4<author><![CDATA[Callum Borchers]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购/合并/持股</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>美式足球</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购</category><category>合并</category><category>持股</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>美式足球</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Perfection Trap’ Review: The Enemy of the Good]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>完美主义似乎是我们这个时代的决定性特征。它并不总是受到如此高度的重视。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590130023263216024"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832863?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590130023263216024"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">比尔·希维</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:54 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在每次工作面试中，都会有一个时刻，申请人会被要求说出他或她最大的弱点。 “好吧，我不得不说这是我的完美主义”，这是一个聪明的答案，这是一个非常缺乏谦逊的谦虚的自夸。如今，正如托马斯·柯兰（Thomas Curran）在《完美陷阱：拥抱足够好的力量》中所写的那样，这种“弱点”是一种优势。它向未来的雇主保证你对最高标准的承诺，“以不懈的努力、无数的个人牺牲和大量的自我施加压力来计算”。</p><p>完美主义并不总是受到如此高度的重视。它曾经是恐怖的东西。纳撒尼尔·霍桑 (Nathaniel Hawthorne) 于 1843 年创作的警世故事《胎记》讲述了一位科学家对他美丽妻子的唯一缺陷——胎记非常着迷的故事。她将他的厌恶内化，并希望“不惜一切代价”消除这一缺陷。科学家最终配制出了一种治疗方法，他的妻子吞下了它。好吧，除非它会杀了她。课程？完美是一种疯狂，最好避免。</p><p>伦敦经济学院心理学副教授柯兰写道，完美主义“似乎是我们这个时代的决定性特征”。我们日复一日的工作生活充满了这样的观念：“如果你偷懒、放慢速度，或者更糟糕的是，花点时间简单地思考所有无情的磨砺到底是为了什么，那么你就会被淘汰。”被留下来。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/2afcee72-ced3-4242-8443-c43974c673a1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>我本以为《完美陷阱》会用可预见的正念大杂烩，再加上一点认知行为疗法，也许还加入了一款手机应用程序，来攻击完美主义者（作者自己也算作完美主义者）的弄巧成拙的行为。相反，柯兰先生发表了一份宣言，谴责我们的经济体系创造和维持了一套扭曲的价值观，这些价值观推动了完美主义，这些价值观是我们未经审查就内化的。他警告说，没有简单的解决办法。这项任务需要进行深刻的反思，这既困难又不受欢迎。我们必须面对“我们对现代社会‘伟大’和‘善良’的最基本假设。”</p><p>兰斯·阿姆斯特朗的例子就是这种动态的例证。这位自行车手承认使用兴奋剂赢得了七次环法自行车赛胜利，但并不为此感到遗憾——在他看来，这只是为了公平竞争。 “文化就是这样，”他告诉奥普拉·温弗瑞。 “我们都是成年人，我们都做出了自己的选择。”但柯兰先生告诉我们，退后一步，看看阿姆斯特朗先生如何试图使非理性和令人震惊的行为正常化。他自愿参加的军备竞赛冒着每个自行车手的健康风险，但并没有使任何一个骑手更有可能取得成功。阿姆斯特朗先生的努力得到了回报，但并不是每个人都那么幸运，一些骑自行车的人失去了健康，另一些则失去了生命。</p><p> “同样的破坏性军备竞赛现在正在更广泛的文化中上演，”柯兰先生写道。我们让自己的福祉屈服于经济的福祉，经济“需要的增长远远超过我们感到满足的需要。完美主义只是附带损害。”柯兰先生的观点很明确。对他来说，健康的完美主义——我们这些人试图将自己排除在他的批评之外的一种限制——是一种矛盾的说法。</p><p>我们的经济建立在一些不可靠的假设之上。作者告诉我们，基本思想是不断增加的商品和服务供应推动经济增长。更多的供应意味着更多的需求。更多的需求意味着更多的利润。更多的利润意味着更多的就业机会。旋转体必须保持旋转。</p><p>广告和社交媒体利用每一个机会提醒我们我们有多么缺乏，从而刺激了需求。解决办法是买更多的东西——新车、更大的房子、更好的小玩意、更时髦的衣服、更昂贵的化妆品。我一直对这些力量有一种模糊的感觉，但我从未见过这个理论如此简洁地阐述过。正如作者所写，“一旦你看到了广告运作的赤字模式，你就无法忽视它。”</p><p>社交媒体和广告的命脉是不快乐。每天，约有 20 亿人（地球人口的四分之一）登录<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a></p>或Instagram，并衡量我们的生活与那些过着美好生活的人们的照片相比，有哪些不足之处。 “这不正是 Instagram 的主要用途吗？”一名 Instagram 员工在一份泄露的备忘录中反问道。 “最上0.1%的人的（非常上镜的）生活？” It is.当孩子们感觉自己达不到要求时，他们会付出特别高的代价。根据泄露的 Facebook 演示文稿中的一张幻灯片，“我们使三分之一的青少年女孩的身体形象问题变得更加严重”。<p></p><p>更令人不安的是，一份泄露的图表显示，6% 的美国青少年和 13% 的英国青少年表示，“花时间在 Instagram 上是他们想要自杀的原因之一。”该公司没有动力去解决这个问题。 “Facebook（现在的 Meta）”（Instagram 的母公司）“自 2009 年以来，其广告收入呈指数级增长，如今已达到近 1150 亿美元，”Curran 先生提醒我们。它并没有告诉我们我们现在的样子很好。 “他们的算法甚至可以精确定位年轻人‘需要增强信心’的时刻。 ”</p><p> 《完美陷阱》是一本奇怪且不完美的书。 30岁出头的运动心理学家并不是每天都会掌管整个全球经济。其中的图表非常糟糕，就像逃脱了机构官僚机构的 PowerPoint 幻灯片一样。作者要求你接受自己所有独特且不完美的荣耀，这实在是太恰当了。完美主义在我们的生活中根深蒂固。除了政治行动之外，他没有提供明确的前进道路。但也许这些事情不是他的工作。作为对完美主义破坏性幻觉如何产生的解释，以及对创造这种幻觉的经济的批判，这是一本重要的书。柯兰先生希望有一天，我们可以重新发现意大利那句古老谚语的真理：“适可而止。”</p><p><em>希维先生是马里兰州贝塞斯达的一位作家。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>托马斯·柯兰</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>